<div class="section-newsletters "><div class="spacer-bottom-15"><div class="section-heading">Free Newsletters</div>
<div class="js-newsletter" data-newsletterurl="/ct/channel/ajax/newsletter.html"><div class="spacer-bottom-10 spacer-top-10"><a class="section-heading_sm" href="/myaccount/?page=newsletters">Get the best from CT editors, delivered straight to your inbox!</a><img src="/system/newsletters/img/question_mark.gif" class="tooltip nlList_item_info" title="Stay informed with updates from CT Direct, CT Weekly, CT Women and Books & Culture newsletters" /></div>
<input type="hidden" name="source" value="Christianity-Today-Inline" /><input type="text" value="Email Address" name="email" class="form-elements_input clearField form-elements inputBox" /><input type="image" class="js-getNewsletter" value="submit" name="submit" src="/ct/channel/img/btn_go_lg.gif" /></div>
</div>
<a href="/myaccount/?page=newsletters" class="more color-red uppercase">More Newsletters</a></div>
</div><p class="text">Imagine you&rsquo;re standing near the site of the World Trade Center on September 11, 2001. What thoughts and feelings would you experience? Almost all Americans who were alive during the attacks remember where they were on that fateful day and what it felt like to watch the news repeatedly show the buildings&rsquo; collapse. The experiences undergirding the Old Testament texts aren&rsquo;t much different. At least one disturbing event for society at large&mdash;from natural disaster or military invasion to national exile or political scandal&mdash;lies behind almost every Old Testament writing.</p>
<p class="text">It&rsquo;s no surprise, then, that the Old Testament is <a href="https://www.biblegateway.com/quicksearch/?quicksearch=%22fear+not%22&amp;qs_version=KJV" class="">more saturated</a> with the Bible&rsquo;s famous &ldquo;fear not&rdquo; statements than the New Testament. These documents distill the wisdom of centuries, ushering us into the counsel of the eldest elders and the wisest sages to learn what it means to trust in God.</p>
<h4 class="subhead">Showing Solidarity</h4>
<p class="text">One of the ways the Old Testament brings comfort to the anxious is by its dependence on two personable literary genres. The first is historical narrative, which is found in books like Genesis or Joshua. Unlike some social media profiles that are carefully crafted to present only the best, most exciting, and successful sides of a person, these narratives reveal a more complete picture. Characters are presented with both achievements and frailties. There is Moses, the scared speaker (Ex. 4:10); Ahaz, the desperate monarch (2 Kings 16:7); and Naomi, the bitter mother-in-law (Ruth 1:20&ndash;21). These characters remove the stigma of anxiety and remind us that God works through broken people.</p>
<p class="text">The Psalms complement the narratives by offering snapshots of individuals responding to anxiety. Rather than a tidy summary packaged for retrospective sharing, David&rsquo;s penetrating question, &ldquo;How long, Lord?&rdquo; (Ps. 13:1), invites us into his active suffering and gives us permission to plead with God to end our suffering, too. Asaph expresses the inexpressible when he says that God has given him only &ldquo;the bread of tears&rdquo; (Ps. 80:5). Most importantly, this group of human voices provides theological solutions: &ldquo;The Lord is with me; I will not be afraid. What can mere mortals do to me?&rdquo; (Ps. 118:6). The comfort of the Psalms is especially felt by recalling that they are songs meant to be sung and they are the inspired Word of God. This means, as John Calvin noted, that when we sing the Psalms during trials, it is as though God&rsquo;s Spirit is singing through us.</p>
<p class="text">Of course, the texts of the Old Testament don&rsquo;t always seem like a good resource for fighting anxiety. There are moments that feel like a literary gut punch, including Micah&rsquo;s promise of judgment on the people of Israel (Mic. 2:3&ndash;5), and stories of severe testing, such as Abraham&rsquo;s near sacrifice of Isaac (Gen. 22:1&ndash;18). Far from comforting us, these texts only <em>increase</em> our anxiety. But if we read them closely, we find that each story is redemptive because the anxiety is momentary and meant to draw us closer to God in faith and hope. It&rsquo;s never the intent of a biblical author to constantly tease a believer&rsquo;s fears or to pry away their faith in a good God.</p>
<h4 class="subhead">Posing the Existential Question</h4>
<p class="text">After sharing stories and offering reassurance, Old Testament texts often issue a challenge: Will you enact the faith that you profess? It may seem trite, but it&rsquo;s exactly what we need to hear if anxiety is at least partly the product of our will&mdash;a habit of mind that can be <a href="https://www.amazon.com/Finding-Quiet-Overcoming-Anxiety-Practices/dp/031059720X" class="">counteracted</a>. When I was visiting a professional for strength-based counseling, this was the issue he kept discussing with me. &ldquo;Isn&rsquo;t your God one of infinite love and care? How does <em>that</em> relate to your anxiety?&rdquo; It&rsquo;s unsettling to have a non-Christian pressing you on the disconnect between your orthodoxy and your orthopraxy, but he was right. You can only say the Serenity Prayer for so long before the line &ldquo;courage to change the things I can&rdquo; becomes less of a statement and more of <br>an imperative.</p><div class="align-center spacer-bottom-15 clearfix"><span class="article-divider">Article continues below</span><div class="spacer-bottom-20 clearfix bg-ad-gray "><figure>
<script type="text/javascript">
if (!pageNum) { var pageNum = Math.round(Math.random() * 100000000); }
document.write('<scr'); 
